# Overview

I have a `Customer` entity with an embedded collection of `Order`s. `Customer`s and `Order`s are updated using  separate Spring Data JPA repositories (`CustomerRepository` &amp; `OrderRepository`).

The following operations are performed within a transactional method:

1. An order is added for a customer using the `OrderRepository`&#39;s `save` method

2. The customer is read using the `CustomerRepository`&#39;s `findById` method

Expected result: The customer contains the order

Actual result: The customer does *NOT* contain the order

# Sample Project

- https://github.com/fmck3516/jpa-update-embedded-collection 
- Hibernate 6.1.7.Final
- Spring Boot Version 3.0.4

# Details

Customer:

```
@Entity
public class Customer {

    @Id
    String id;

    @OneToMany(mappedBy = &quot;customer&quot;)
    List&lt;Order&gt; orders;

}
```

Order:

```
@Entity
@Table(name = &quot;orders&quot;)
public class Order {

    @Id
    String id;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = &quot;customer_id&quot;, nullable = false)
    Customer customer;

}
```

I use Spring Data repositories for read/write operations:

```
@Repository
public interface CustomerRepository extends JpaRepository&lt;Customer, String&gt; {
}
```

```
@Repository
public interface OrderRepository extends JpaRepository&lt;Order, String&gt; {
}
```

Updates to the embedded orders collection using the `OrderRepository` are not reflected on the customer entity:

```
Customer customer = new Customer();
customer.id = &quot;customer-0&quot;;

customer = customerRepository.save(customer);

Order order = new Order();
order.id = &quot;order-0&quot;;
order.customer = customer;

orderRepository.save(order);

System.out.println(customerRepository.findById(&quot;customer-0&quot;));
```

Expected Output:

`Optional[Customer{id=&#39;customer-0&#39;, orders=[Order{id=&#39;order-0&#39;, customer=customer-0}]}]`

Actual Output:

`Optional[Customer{id=&#39;customer-0&#39;, orders=null}]`

I&#39;m aware of the following solutions / workarounds:

- Replace `save` with `saveAndFlush` and use `EntityManager` to refresh the customer object: This will generate the expected output.

- Assign the order to the customer. Save the order and the customer.

- Re-read the customer in a new transaction.

Unfortunately, I&#39;m dealing with an existing code base where database access is scattered. It is not trivial to implement any of those alternatives.

Is there a way to tell JPA to &quot;auto-magically&quot; update the `Customer` entity whenever the embedded `Order` collection is updated via the `OrderRepository`?

