I stumbled upon this issue with codebase compiled for Java 11. Trial and error led me to discover that a method recursed infinitely before throwing an exception (which was caught and a nice text was concatenated to report it). Apparently `StringConcatFactory` could not work in this situation; as a quick check, explicitly using `StringBuilder` did work, roughly like this:

    ...} catch (Exception e) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder()
					.append(&quot;Got some problem: &quot;)
                    .append(e.getMessage());
        System.err.println(sb.toString());
        //System.err.println(&quot;Got some problem: &quot; + e.getMessage()); // fails
    }

Although in this case of course the proper solution was to break the infinite loop.

I suppose the factory failed to work because the loop ate all resources on the heap, or something of the sort.

